default&#xa0;
defaultNon-dependant deductionsdefault&#xa0;default2.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultN
defaulton-dependant deductions (N
defaultD
defaultDs) are reductions in housing costs eligible for HB and SMI,
default based on assumed 
default(not actual) 
defaultcontributions from “non-dependants” such as grown-up children and elderly relatives. 
defaultThe
default non-dependant is under no obligation to make these payments or to disclose their own financial details. Logically, one would expect non-dependants themselves to be able to claim HB to help them pay the assumed contribution, but in fact they cannot.
default&#xa0;
default2.13
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNDDs
default 
defaultcause various problems (of hardship, complexity, reduced housing options and work disincentives)
default. 
defaultT
defaulthe pre
defaultvious Government had frozen them
default for some years, with a view to phasing them out. The current Government has returned to a policy of increasing them, w
defaultell above the rate of inflation.
default&#xa0;
default2.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNDDs are to be restructured (and re-named “housing cost c
defaultontributions”) under
default UC, with an emphasis on reducing work disincentives for the non-dependant, but at the cost of extending their impact elsewhere, notably to many 
defaultyoung unemployed people and their parents.
default&#xa0;
defaultA CAB in the East of England advised an unemployed couple with three dependent children and a 20-year-old daughter earning £210 per week gross. 
defaultT
defaulthe daughter was not meeting the NDD. A suspended possession order 
defaultwas eventually made, the arrears partly resulting from the NDD. The daughter has since taken out a loan to make back payments. The total weekly rent is £90 and it seems unreasonable that over 40 per cent of this should be payable by the daughter (who share
defaults a bedroom with a younger sister).
default&#xa0;
defaultLocalised Council Tax Supportdefault&#xa0;default2.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe abolition of Council Tax Benefit and its replacement with cash-limited localised relief is expected to create a scenario
default in England
default in which people on very low incomes will be required
default to pay small amounts of council tax that they cannot afford, creating major problems of collection, enforcement and debt
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.16
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal tapers (withdrawal rates) will also potentially overlap with the UC taper, causing high marginal deduction rates across the a
defaultffected part of the income scale
default, 
defaulta problem which UC was supposed to solve.
default The original intention was that CTB would become part of UC – a coherence that has now been lost.
default&#xa0;
defaultA CAB in 
defaultLondon
default advised a single, disabled man with a
defaultn artificial leg. He lived
default i
defaultn 2-bedroom council accommodation
default, receiving
default Income Support and Disability Living Allowance
default (DLA)
default. His HB ha
defaultd
default been reduced by 14 per cent under
default the size restrictions and he was
default now li
defaultable to pay 15 per cent of his council t
defaultax.
default This meant he now had
default to find
default £60 per month towards h
defaultis rent and £10.60 towards his council t
defaultax. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCumulative impactsdefault&#xa0;
default2.17
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCuts to a range of benefits will oft
defaulten affect
default the same individuals and families, having a multiple impact and causing considerable hardship. This is a neglected issue and is not adequately monitored. HB rides on top of other benefits and is received by the full range of claimant groups, so will featu
defaultre strongly in multiple impacts – as will the rental element of UC. 
defaultThe case examples at paragraphs 2.10, 2.11 and 2.16 illustrate this.
default&#xa0;
default2.18
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProposals for 
defaultbenefit legislation should therefore be accompanied by a poverty impact assessment sufficiently sophisti
defaultcated to provide estimates of multiple impacts.
default&#xa0;
defaultPayment of HB/ UC to tenantsdefault rather than direct to landlordsdefault&#xa0;
default2.19
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlready the default position for HB in the private rented sector, it is intended that this will
default be the case in all sectors as
default UC is introduced. 
default&#xa0;
default2.20
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA number of “demonstration projects” are under way to test this approach. There will be exceptions, relating to vulnerability and/ or rent arrears. It is expected that arrears will be a significant problem. 
default&#xa0;
default2.21
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIndeed, the demonstration projects have alr
defaultead
defaulty shown this to be the
default case: the most recent report monitoring
default the six project areas 
defaultcommented that: 
default“
defaultcollection rates are lower in all project areas than before the (demonstration projects) went live. And more of the rent that is paid arrives in instalmen
defaultts through the month (i.e. late) rather than on time in one sum as it did when Housing Benefit was paid by the local authority direct to the landlord. Landlord income and cash flow has, therefore, reduced. A small percentage rise in arrears represents sign
defaultificant funds for landlords”
default. 
default&#xa0;
default2.22
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhen direct payments
default to tenants
